AGI - The first president of the Republic to celebrate April 25 was Luigi Einaudi, in 1950, two years after his election, but the image that will remain in the long history is that of Sergio Mattarella who, alone and with the mask, lays a crown at the Altar of the Homeland during the Covid epidemic. Over the years all presidents celebrated the Liberation Day, those with traditional ceremonies, those with speeches and those visiting symbolic places for our Republic. The date was chosen by Alcide De Gasperi>, secretary of the Dc who led the provisional government, with a decree countersigned on April 22, 1946 by Prince Umberto of Savoy, General Lieutenant of the Kingdom: "To celebrate the total liberation of the Italian territory, 25 April 1946 is declared a national holiday". So not the day of the end of the war, but that in which the National Liberation Committee of Alta Italy (CLNAI), which had its seat in Milan and was chaired by Alfredo Pizzoni together with Luigi Longo and the future president of the Republic Sandro Pertini, had proclaimed the general insurrection in the territories still occupied by the Nazis.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
In the early years after the end of the war, thanks to the climate of national unity, the celebrations were shared by all parties present to the government, but after the end of the government of national solidarity and the defeat of the Left in the elections of 1948, the celebrations differed. It was then, however, that it intervened a law, the 260 of May 27, 1949, to establish that between the "festive recurrences" of the new Italy there would be, in addition to the traditional dates such as Christmas and Easter and the 2 June Festa della Repubblica, on April 25 as "anniversary of liberation" >. In the long debate at the House, which was then presided over by the future president of the Republic Giovanni Gronchi, the most discussed element was the proposal to include also the date of the Breccia di Porta Pia, but was considered too divisive and rejected, while Giorgio Almirante also expressed himself against the choice of April 25. The following year, on the first occasion after the establishment of the law, Einaudi celebrated the feast giving the city of Reggio Emilia the Gold Medal to the Military Valor, while on the 10th anniversary of Liberation, 1955, he chose to celebrate first in Genoa and then in Milan in an official event preceded by the mass of Archbishop Montini, future Pope Paul VI. Since then the celebrations were increasingly institutional, with President of the Republic and President of the Council engaged in official ceremonies.
&nbsp;
On April 22, 1955, John Gronchi, then President of the House who would be elected President of the Republic twenty days later, gave a speech in the courtroom which was then published in the albi of all the municipalities of Italy. The following year the date coincided with an official trip to Gronchi in France; the concurrent between 25 April and a trip abroad repeated in 1969, when Giuseppe Saragat flew to London, and in 1986 when Francesco Cossiga went to Berlin for a visit to West Germany. Saragat, in 1970, joined the traditional ceremony at the Altar of the Homeland, a visit to the Fosse Ardeatine and then a speech at the Quirinale.> The same choice, Altare della Patria e Fosse Ardeatine, was also replicated by Francesco Cossiga, then by Oscar Luigi Scalfaro and Carlo Azeglio Ciampi. Giovanni Leone also sticks to tradition and to him he touched to speak in one of the most dramatic 25 April of the history of the Republic, a few days after the abduction of Aldo Moro in 1978.
< blockquote
&nbsp;
"In the lives of people there are moments of darkness, moments that seem desperate and our people have known. But when he found unity of intent he also knew through bitter and bloody struggles, writing in history bright dates like the Liberation that we celebrate today" (John Leo)
</blockquote
&nbsp;
Sandro Pertini, from whose voice on the radio the Italians listened to the order to resist on April 25, 1945, elected president of the Republic in 1978, always tried to celebrate the Feast of Liberation among young people, sometimes pupils other times military, to spur them to defend democracy and freedom. His successor, Cossiga, was devoted to tradition, but only a few days after his term of office, on April 25, 1992, he broke out the normal Liturgy of Liberation, leaving in advance with a speech to unified networks "to better serve the Republic". And also the celebrations of April 25 were marked: in 1994, after the victory in the political elections of Silvio Berlusconi, ally of An and Lega, the center left the anti-fascist root of resistance, at the Anpi court in Milan also participated the leadership of the Carroccio that received some whistles. Bossi minimized the anti-fascist spirit of his party. Scalfaro, elected two years earlier, is the most traditional of the celebrations.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Later, Scalfaro has intervened several times to define April 25 as an event involving the entire Italian people, while peacekeeping assumes the condemnation of dictatorship, with a distinction between historical responsibility and human reconciliation, in which everyone is commemorated with respect. Ciampi in his seven-year-old promoted a shared reading of the Liberation Day, reaffirming the inseparable link between the Resistance, the choice of the Republic after the referendum of 2 June 1946 and the entry into force of the Constitution, fundamental law of free and democratic Italy, a commitment that had seen both the Allies and the partisans and the entire Italian people with a patriotic-resorgimental perspective. An ever greater openness to reconciliation, albeit with the clear divisions between reasons and twists, came from Giorgio Napolitano. In addition to the traditional ceremonies, the then president in 2007 flew to Kefalonia to reiterate that Liberation "is the feast of all Italians" and for several years visited places symbol of the Resistance, beginning with Saint Anne of Stazzema. Two years later in Onna, Silvio Berlusconi joined the procession of the Epi.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
On April 25, Sergio Mattarella coincided with a historical date, the 70th anniversary of Liberation, which the President wanted to celebrate in Milan defining that passage of history as the "ethical foundation of our nation", > a concept reiterated several times to refute attempts to revisionism. "Now and always Resistance" marked last year in a long speech from Cuneo. First Milan, then Varallo Sesia, Fossoli, the fascist civil concentration camp of Casoli, Vittorio Veneto, Acerra were the places chosen over the years by the President to remember that the whole country contributed to the fight against Nazi fascism, but the image that will remain for all in the eyes is that of its solitary descent from the Altar of the Homeland, with the mask, while Italy was in Locknsp for Covid.
&nbsp;
